[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] It’s been available across browsers since January 2019.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] The Streams API allows JavaScript to programmatically access streams of data received over the network and process them as desired by the developer.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Streaming involves breaking a resource that you want to receive over a network down into small chunks, then processing it bit by bit.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Browsers already do this when receiving media assets — videos buffer and play as more of the content downloads, and sometimes you'll see images display gradually as more is loaded too.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] But this capability has never been available to JavaScript before.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Previously, if we wanted to process a resource of some kind (video, text file, etc.), we'd have to download the entire file, wait for it to be deserialized into a suitable format, then process all the data.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] With the Streams API, you can start processing raw data with JavaScript bit by bit, as soon as it is available, without needing to generate a buffer, string, or blob.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] (The basic concept of the stream API is data is fetched from the network in several data packets.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] There are more advantages too — you can detect when streams start or end, chain streams together, handle errors and cancel streams as required, and react to the speed at which the stream is being read.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] The usage of Streams hinges on making responses available as streams.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] For example, the response body returned by a successful fetch request is a `ReadableStream` that can be read by a reader created with `ReadableStream.getReader()`.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] More complicated uses involve creating your own stream using the `ReadableStream()` constructor, for example to process data inside a service worker.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] You can also write data to streams using `WritableStream`.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] It can be used to handle response streams of the Fetch API, or developer-defined streams (e.g., a custom `ReadableStream()` constructor).
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Represents a default reader that can be used to read stream data supplied from a network (e.g., a fetch request).
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Represents a controller allowing control of a `ReadableStream`'s state and internal queue.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Default controllers are for streams that are not byte streams.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Provides a standard abstraction for writing streaming data to a destination, known as a sink.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] This object comes with built-in backpressure and queuing.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Represents a default writable stream writer that can be used to write chunks of data to a writable stream.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Represents a controller allowing control of a `WritableStream`'s state.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] When constructing a `WritableStream`, the underlying sink is given a corresponding `WritableStreamDefaultController` instance to manipulate.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Represents an abstraction for a stream object that transforms data as it passes through a pipe chain of stream objects.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Provides methods to manipulate the `ReadableStream` and `WritableStream` associated with a transform stream.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Provides a built-in byte length queuing strategy that can be used when constructing streams.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Provides a built-in chunk counting queuing strategy that can be used when constructing streams.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] When a new `Request` object is constructed, you can pass it a `ReadableStream` in the `body` property of its `RequestInit` dictionary.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] This `Request` could then be passed to a `fetch()` to commence fetching the stream.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] The response body returned by a successful fetch request is exposed by default as a `ReadableStream`, and can have a reader attached to it, etc.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Represents a BYOB ("bring your own buffer") reader that can be used to read stream data supplied by the developer (e.g., a custom `ReadableStream()` constructor).
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Byte stream controllers are for byte streams.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] Represents a pull into request in a `ReadableByteStreamController`.
[src:rxjs-observable/api-streams-api] We have created a directory of examples to go along with the Streams API documentation — see mdn/dom-examples/streams.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Iterators and Generators bring the concept of iteration directly into the core language and provide a mechanism for customizing the behavior of `for...of` loops.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] In JavaScript an **iterator** is an object which defines a sequence and potentially a return value upon its termination.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] The next value in the iteration sequence.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] This is `true` if the last value in the sequence has already been consumed.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] If `value` is present alongside `done`, it is the iterator's return value.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Once created, an iterator object can be iterated explicitly by repeatedly calling `next()`.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Iterating over an iterator is said to consume the iterator, because it is generally only possible to do once.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] After a terminating value has been yielded additional calls to `next()` should continue to return `{done: true}`.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] The most common iterator in JavaScript is the Array iterator, which returns each value in the associated array in sequence.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] While it is easy to imagine that all iterators could be expressed as arrays, this is not true.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Arrays must be allocated in their entirety, but iterators are consumed only as necessary.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Because of this, iterators can express sequences of unlimited size, such as the range of integers between `0` and `Infinity`.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Here is an example which can do just that.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] It allows creation of a range iterator which defines a sequence of integers from `start` (inclusive) to `end` (exclusive) spaced `step` apart.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Its final return value is the size of the sequence it created, tracked by the variable `iterationCount`.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] While custom iterators are a useful tool, their creation requires careful programming due to the need to explicitly maintain their internal state.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] **Generator functions** provide a powerful alternative: they allow you to define an iterative algorithm by writing a single function whose execution is not continuous.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Generator functions are written using the `function*` syntax.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] When called, generator functions do not initially execute their code.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Instead, they return a special type of iterator, called a **Generator**.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] When a value is consumed by calling the generator's `next` method, the Generator function executes until it encounters the `yield` keyword.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] The function can be called as many times as desired, and returns a new Generator each time.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Each Generator may only be iterated once.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] We can now adapt the example from above.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] The behavior of this code is identical, but the implementation is much easier to write and read.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] An object is **iterable** if it defines its iteration behavior, such as what values are looped over in a `for...of` construct.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Some built-in types, such as `Array` or `Map`, have a default iteration behavior, while other types (such as `Object`) do not.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] In order to be **iterable**, an object must implement the `[Symbol.iterator]()` method.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] This means that the object (or one of the objects up its prototype chain) must have a property with a `Symbol.iterator` key.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] It may be possible to iterate over an iterable more than once, or only once.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] It is up to the programmer to know which is the case.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Iterables which can iterate only once (such as Generators) customarily return `this` from their `[Symbol.iterator]()` method, whereas iterables which can be iterated many times must return a new iterator on each invocation of `[Symbol.iterator]()`.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] User-defined iterables can be used in `for...of` loops or the spread syntax as usual.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] `String`, `Array`, `TypedArray`, `Map` and `Set` are all built-in iterables, because their prototype objects all have a `Symbol.iterator` method.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Some statements and expressions expect iterables.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] For example: the `for...of` loops, spread syntax, `yield*`, and destructuring syntax.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Generators compute their `yield`ed values *on demand*, which allows them to efficiently represent sequences that are expensive to compute (or even infinite sequences, as demonstrated above).
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] The `next()` method also accepts a value, which can be used to modify the internal state of the generator.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] A value passed to `next()` will be received by `yield`.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] You can force a generator to throw an exception by calling its `throw()` method and passing the exception value it should throw.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] This exception will be thrown from the current suspended context of the generator, as if the `yield` that is currently suspended were instead a `throw value` statement.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] If the exception is not caught from within the generator, it will propagate up through the call to `throw()`, and subsequent calls to `next()` will result in the `done` property being `true`.
[src:rxjs-observable/iterators-and-generators] Generators have a `return()` method that returns the given value and finishes the generator itself.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The subject knows its observers through a standardized interface and manages the subscription list directly.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This pattern creates a one-to-many dependency where multiple observers can listen to a single subject, but the coupling is typically synchronous and direct—the subject calls observer methods when changes occur, though asynchronous implementations using event queues are possible.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Unlike the publish-subscribe pattern, there is no intermediary broker; the subject and observers have direct references to each other.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] It is commonly used to implement event handling systems in event-driven programming, particularly in-process systems like GUI toolkits or MVC frameworks.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This makes the pattern well-suited to processing data that arrives unpredictably—such as user input, HTTP requests, GPIO signals, updates from distributed databases, or changes in a GUI model.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The observer design pattern is a behavioural pattern listed among the 23 well-known "Gang of Four" design patterns that address recurring design challenges in order to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, yielding objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The naive approach would be for one object (subject) to directly call specific methods on each dependent object.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This creates tight coupling because the subject must know the concrete types and specific interfaces of all dependent objects, making the code inflexible and hard to extend.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] However, this direct approach may be preferable in performance-critical scenarios (such as low-level kernel structures or real-time systems) where the overhead of abstraction is unacceptable and compile-time optimization is crucial.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] When a subject changes state, all registered observers are notified and updated automatically.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The subject manages its own state while also maintaining a list of observers and notifying them of state changes by calling their `update()` operation.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The responsibility of observers is to register and unregister themselves with a subject (in order to be notified of state changes) and to update their state (to synchronize it with the subject's state) when they are notified.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This approach makes subject and observers loosely coupled through interface standardization.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The subject only needs to know that observers implement the `update()` method—it has no knowledge of observers' concrete types or internal implementation details.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Observers can be added and removed independently at run time.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The observer pattern and the publish–subscribe pattern are closely related and often confused, as both support one-to-many communication between components.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] However, they differ significantly in architecture, degree of coupling, and common use cases.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] In practice, publish–subscribe systems evolved to address several limitations of the observer pattern.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] A typical observer implementation creates a tight coupling between the subject and its observers.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This may limit scalability, flexibility, and maintainability, especially in distributed environments.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Subjects and observers must conform to a shared interface, and both parties are aware of each other’s presence.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] To reduce this coupling, publish–subscribe systems introduce a message broker or event bus that intermediates between publishers and subscribers.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This additional layer removes the need for direct references, allowing systems to evolve independently.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Brokers may also support features like message persistence, delivery guarantees, topic-based filtering, and asynchronous communication.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] In some systems, the observer pattern is used internally to implement subscription mechanisms behind a publish–subscribe interface.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] In other cases, the patterns are applied independently.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] For example, JavaScript libraries and frameworks often offer both observer-like subscriptions (e.g., via callback registration) and decoupled pub-sub mechanisms (e.g., via event emitters or signals).
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Historically, in early graphical operating systems like OS/2 and Microsoft Windows, the terms "publish–subscribe" and "event-driven programming" were often used as synonyms for the observer pattern.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The observer pattern, as formalized in *Design Patterns*, deliberately omits concerns such as unsubscription, notification filtering, delivery guarantees, and message logging.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] These advanced capabilities are typically implemented in robust message queuing systems, where the observer pattern may serve as a foundational mechanism but is not sufficient by itself.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Related patterns include mediator and singleton.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] A common drawback of the observer pattern is the potential for memory leaks, known as the lapsed listener problem.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This occurs when a subject maintains strong references to its observers, preventing them from being garbage collected even if they are no longer needed elsewhere.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Because the pattern typically requires both explicit registration and deregistration (as in the dispose pattern), forgetting to unregister observers can leave dangling references.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This issue can be mitigated by using weak references for observer references, allowing the garbage collector to reclaim observer objects that are no longer in use.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] In some applications, particularly user interfaces, the subject's state may change so frequently that notifying observers on every change is inefficient or counterproductive.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] For example, a view that re-renders on every minor change in a data model might become unresponsive or flicker.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] In such cases, the observer pattern can be modified to decouple notifications *temporally* by introducing a throttling mechanism, such as a timer.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Rather than updating on every state change, the observer polls the subject or is notified at regular intervals, rendering an approximate but stable view of the model.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This approach is commonly used for elements like progress bars, where the underlying process changes state rapidly.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Instead of responding to every minor increment, the observer updates the visual display periodically, improving performance and usability.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This form of temporal decoupling allows observers to remain responsive without being overwhelmed by high-frequency updates, while still reflecting the overall trend or progress of the subject’s state.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] In this UML class diagram, the `Subject` class does not update the state of dependent objects directly.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Instead, `Subject` refers to the `Observer` interface (`update()`) for updating state, which makes the `Subject` independent of how the state of dependent objects is updated.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The `Observer1` and `Observer2` classes implement the `Observer` interface by synchronizing their state with subject's state.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] The UML sequence diagram shows the runtime interactions: The `Observer1` and `Observer2` objects call `attach(this)` on `Subject1` to register themselves.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Assuming that the state of `Subject1` changes, `Subject1` calls `notify()` on itself.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] `notify()` calls `update()` on the registered `Observer1` and `Observer2`objects, which request the changed data (`getState()`) from `Subject1` to update (synchronize) their state.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] While the library classes `java.util.Observer` and `java.util.Observable` exist, they have been deprecated in Java 9 because the model implemented was quite limited.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] Below is an example written in Java that takes keyboard input and handles each input line as an event.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] When a string is supplied from `System.in`, the method `notifyObservers()` is then called in order to notify all observers of the event's occurrence, in the form of an invocation of their update methods.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] C# provides the `IObservable`. and `IObserver` interfaces as well as documentation on how to implement the design pattern.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] JavaScript has a deprecated `Object.observe` function that was a more accurate implementation of the observer pattern.
[src:rxjs-observable/observer-pattern] This would fire events upon change to the observed object.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] ReactiveX is an API for asynchronous programming with observable streams.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Asynchronous programming allows programmers to call functions and then have the functions "callback" when they are done, usually by giving the function the address of another function to execute when it is done.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Programs designed in this way often avoid the overhead of having many threads constantly starting and stopping.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Observable streams (i.e. streams that can be observed) in the context of Reactive Extensions are like event emitters that emit three events: next, error, and complete.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] An observable emits next events until it either emits an error event or a complete event.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] However, at that point it will not emit any more events, unless it is subscribed to again.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The examples below use the RxJS implementation of Reactive Extensions for the JavaScript programming language.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] For sequences of data, it combines the advantages of iterators with the flexibility of event-based asynchronous programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] It also works as a simple promise, eliminating the pyramid of doom that results from multiple layers of callbacks.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] ReactiveX is a combination of ideas from the observer and the iterator patterns and from functional programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] An observer subscribes to an observable sequence.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The sequence then sends the items to the observer one at a time, usually by calling the provided callback function.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The observer handles each one before processing the next one.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] If many events come in asynchronously, they must be stored in a queue or dropped.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] In ReactiveX, an observer will never be called with an item out of order or (in a multi-threaded context) called before the callback has returned for the previous item.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Asynchronous calls remain asynchronous and may be handled by returning an observable.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] It is similar to the iterators pattern in that if a fatal error occurs, it notifies the observer separately (by calling a second function).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] When all the items have been sent, it completes (and notifies the observer by calling a third function).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The Reactive Extensions API also borrows many of its operators from iterator operators in other programming languages.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] An operator is a function that takes one observable (the source) as its first argument and returns another observable (the destination, or outer observable).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Then for every item that the source observable emits, it will apply a function to that item, and then emit it on the destination Observable.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] It can even emit another Observable on the destination observable.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] An operator that emits inner observables can be followed by another operator that in some way combines the items emitted by all the inner observables and emits the item on its outer observable.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Operators can be chained together to create complex data flows that filter events based on certain criteria.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Multiple operators can be applied to the same observable.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Some of the operators that can be used in Reactive Extensions may be familiar to programmers who use functional programming language, such as map, reduce, group, and zip.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] There are many other operators available in Reactive Extensions, though the operators available in a particular implementation for a programming language may vary.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Here is an example of using the map and reduce operators.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] We create an observable from a list of numbers.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The map operator will then multiply each number by two and return an observable.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The reduce operator will then sum up all the numbers provided to it (the value of 0 is the starting point).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Calling subscribe will register an *observer* that will observe the values from the observable produced by the chain of operators.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] With the subscribe method, we are able to pass in an error-handling function, called whenever an error is emitted in the observable, and a completion function when the observable has finished emitting items.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Certain RxJS primitives such as `BehaviorSubject` make it possible to create pure stateful streams to track application state of arbitrary complexity in simple terms.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The button below will feed an event to the stream, which in turn will re-emit the next natural number every time, back into the `<span>` tag that follows and displays the count of clicks detected.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Reactive Extensions was created by the Cloud Programmability Team at Microsoft around 2011, as a byproduct of a larger effort called Volta.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] It was originally intended to provide an abstraction for events across different tiers in an application to support tier splitting in Volta.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The project's logo represents an electric eel, which is a reference to Volta.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The extensions suffix in the name is a reference to the Parallel Extensions technology which was invented around the same time; the two are considered complementary.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The initial implementation of Rx was for .NET Framework and was released on June 21, 2011.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Later, the team started the implementation of Rx for other platforms, including JavaScript and C++.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] The technology was released as open source in late 2012, initially on CodePlex.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-extensions] Later, the code moved to GitHub and has been ported to several other languages, including Go, Java, Kotlin, PHP and Rust.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] Look for RxJS and related packages under the /packages directory.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] Applications like the rxjs.dev documentation site are under the /apps directory.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] Reactive Extensions Library for JavaScript.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] This is a rewrite of Reactive-Extensions/RxJS and is the latest production-ready version of RxJS.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] This rewrite is meant to have better performance, better modularity, better debuggable call stacks, while staying mostly backwards compatible, with some breaking changes that reduce the API surface.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] By contributing or commenting on issues in this repository, whether you've read them or not, you're agreeing to the Contributor Code of Conduct.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] Much like traffic laws, ignorance doesn't grant you immunity.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] Because of this issue we're using `yarn`.
[src:rxjs-observable/reactivex-rxjs] (Basically the docs app uses `@types/jasmine`, and the package uses `@types/mocha` and they get hoisted to the top level by `npm install` with workspaces, and then TypeScript vomits everywhere when you try to build).
